---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'SSDI Misconceptions | ssdicalc.com';
const description = 'Common myths and misconceptions about SSDI eligibility, benefits, and the application process.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>SSDI Misconceptions</h1>
  <h2>"If I can do anything at all, I won't qualify."</h2>
  <p>False. SSA evaluates whether you can do substantial gainful activity (SGA) — defined work activity earning above $1,620/month (2025). Part-time or limited activity doesn't automatically disqualify you if you can't sustain full-time work.</p>
  <h2>"I should wait until I'm really sick to apply."</h2>
  <p>Apply as soon as you become disabled. Benefits are not retroactive beyond 12 months before your application, and the process takes years. Delaying costs money.</p>
  <h2>"Most people get approved on the first try."</h2>
  <p>The opposite is true. About 67% of initial applications are denied. Most successful claimants go through reconsideration and an ALJ hearing, often with attorney representation.</p>
  <h2>"SSDI is welfare."</h2>
  <p>SSDI is an insurance program funded by payroll taxes you paid during your working years. You earned this coverage — it is not a means-tested welfare benefit.</p>
  <h2>"I can't work at all while on SSDI."</h2>
  <p>SSDI has a Trial Work Period allowing you to test your ability to work for up to 9 months without affecting your benefits. Work incentives are designed to encourage recipients to attempt return to work.</p>
</BaseLayout>
